            </div>
            <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="b" xml:lang="grc">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="3"/><persName type="attested"><name>Κόϊντε</name> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <name>Δομίτιε</name></persName>
                    <lb n="4"/>εὐσεβῆ <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> χαῖ<space quantity="1" unit="character"/>ρε
                </ab>
            </div>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp><app><note>Text from autopsy</note></app></listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Quintus Domitius, pious, farewell!
                    Quintus Domitius, pious, farewell!</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#SA">
                <p>Quinto Domizio, pio, addio!
                    Quinto Domizio, pio, addio!</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--Q.Domitei peie | Salve; repeated in Greek: Kointe Domitie | eusebe chaire - but note that a) Q. in Latin is written out in full in the Greek; b) the vocative forms of Domitius are diff; Lat: Domitei; Gr: Domitie; Pius in Latin (written Peie) is tranlsated into Eusebe in Greek (Mommsen thought it a name, but Korhonen thinks epithet). Salve becomes Chaire. Korhonen notes also the absence therefore of cognomen, and so this should be a freeborn individual; furthermore the palaeography suggests to K that the cutter was inexperienced with Latin letters, and k notes the omission of filiation. The slab was the tympanon of a tomb (IMusCat 2 reused in a similar tomb).-->
                    The text shows one of the typical differences between Greek and Latin practice: the name Quintus is
                    abbreviated in the Latin version, but written in full in Greek. pius / eusebes could be a third name
                    (cognomen) or just an epithet: the fact that it is translated rather than transliterated, and the
                    fact that pie salve / eusebe chaire is an attested formula in funerary inscriptions (in Latin,
                    specifically in eastern Sicily) suggests it is an epithet. The forms Domitei and peie (for Domiti
                    and pie) suggest the text was written by someone who was primarily a Greek speaker, since it is a
                    Greek tendency to render long Latin i with ei.</p>
            </div>
